icials, along with some African-American allies, to bring the American model of cotton production to colonial Africa. In a narrative featuring a host of characters -- including British entrepreneurs, African kings, and African-American scientists -- author Jonathan Robins weaves together events in Africa, Britain, and the AmericanSouth. Robins chronicles the origins, failings, and eventual evolution of Britain's colonial cotton project, revealing the global forces and actors that moved and transformed the international cotton industry. JonathanE. Robins is assistant professor of global history at Michigan Technological University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCotton trade--Africa--History. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aModern History. 4aPolitics & Economics. 7aHISTORY / Africa / West.2bisacsh  aAfrican American history.  aAfrican American studies.  acapitalism.  acolonial Africa.  acotton industry.  acotton.  aeconomics.  aglobalization.  ahistory.  apower.  aracism.  aslavery.  atwentieth century history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311143131440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782048510?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782048510423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782048510/original  a978-3-11-143131-4  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles